  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several key ways:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Provide frameworks for national anti-money laundering (AML) legislation\n\n2. Standardization of Legal Approaches\n- Establishing common definitions of money laundering\n- Creating uniform reporting and prevention mechanisms\n- Promoting consistent legal standards across jurisdictions\n\n3. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries cooperate in investigating and prosecuting money laundering\n- Sharing intelligence and evidence\n- Extradition agreements\n- Cross-border legal cooperation\n\n4. Regulatory Compliance\n- International standards require nations to implement specific AML measures\n- Banks and financial institutions must follow global compliance protocols\n- Reporting suspicious transactions internationally\n\n5. Enforcement Mechanisms\n- International sanctions\n- Asset freezing\n- Coordinated investigations\n- Diplomatic pressure to enforce AML regulations\n\n6. Information Sharing\n- Financial intelligence units exchange data\n- Tracking complex international financial transactions\n- Identifying potential money laundering networks\n\nThese interactions create a complex, multilayered approach to combating financial crimes globally.",
